August 12 at 10:54 AM ¬∑

As many of you may have heard, Governor Whitmer and lawmakers are working on a bipartisan plan on Saturday, August 15th to provide a framework for how schools can safely educate students in the fall. These efforts could result in changes to North Branch Area School's Return to Learn Plan, therefore we will be postponing North Branch Elementary's drive-thru meet the teacher night that was scheduled for August 13th and 14th from 3-6. We will reschedule for next week once more information is available - we appreciate your understanding with this last-minute change.

post_text: Reminder for Elementary Families:
shared_text:
NBE
May 27 at 7:00 PM ¬∑

NBE Parents,

On Wednesday, June 3rd and Thursday, June 4th, families will be able to pick up student belongings. This will take place behind the school in the bus mall. Please refer to the following link for the schedule - https://bit.ly/nbepickup. PLEASE NOTE - Along with student belongings, there will be additional documents included such as letters of promotion, certificates, and 4th-grade diplomas. In addition, there may be money included from a previously scheduled Popcorn Friday or field trip.

As a way to assure a timely and safe process, we ask that all families abide by the following guidelines:
Families pick up belongings of all children during the time assigned to the oldest child.
No one (students or parents) will be allowed in the building.
All pick-up will be curbside - please stay in your vehicle at all times.

post_text: Congratulations to our Senior band students!
shared_text:
North Branch Band Boosters is with JAnthony Ehardt and 2 others.
May 28 at 6:13 PM ¬∑

So we did a thing...
‚Ä¢Long post alert‚Ä¢

Once again the class of 2020 has lived through tragic change and shown how resilient they can be.

They all came into the world either right before or in the recent wake of the horrible 9/11/01 and they complete their high school careers during a world wide pandemic.

This tell me these kids will not let anything stop them!

To commemorate their hard work, dedication, endurance, and down right tenacity, we couldn‚Äôt let it just ‚Äúbe done.‚Äù They deserved more and we DELIVERED (literallyüòù).

Today, Mr. Ehardt delivered their senior medals and serenaded them with their fight song. The boosters gifted them with a little basket of goodies to help them remember some of our times we‚Äôve had and to help them a little with whatever life will bring them all in homemade/hometown parade style.

All pics gathered are posted (and some were poached from other parents üòâ).

It was fun to see smiles for once and happy tears flowed free!

Some kids weren‚Äôt home but we hit all that were, and one mom got the surprise instead of the senior.

ENJOY!
(Videos on next post)

post_text: Congratulations to our Quest Graduates!
shared_text:
Quest HS is with Dylan Boven and 2 others.
May 13 at 9:53 AM ¬∑

Presenting the 16th graduating class from Quest High School!

Thank you to Quest High School Principal Mr. Hiltunen for honoring our students with their very own yard sign!

1. Yard signs will be displayed until Friday. You may pick up your yard sign between 4:00-5:30pm on Friday. After Friday, Mr. Rosser will store them at Quest, and you may email him to set up a time to pick them up.

2. Place them in your yard to show your Quest High School pride!

3. Please keep them in the best condition possible, as you will bring them back during graduation rehearsal, and we will display them outside on graduation day. After that, they are yours to keep!

4. Just a reminder, we will be adding a special video honoring our seniors on Thursday night at 7pm!

**We continue to work on setting a graduation day. Our graduation will likely be on either August 6th or 10th. We will decide on a definite day in June, and will post it here on our facebook page.

*IMPORTANT NOTE ABOUT BK-K ROUND UP*
There is an updated Link for the May 19th BK-K Informational Meeting. If you had previously registered for May 19th, we kindly ask that you register again using the link information below. Thank you for your understanding with this technology glitch.

Dear Future BK-K Bronco Families:

Please join North Branch Elementary Principal, Greg Matheson, & Assistant Principal, Theresa Rae, for an optional *virtual meeting* where they will provide information about BK-K Round Up, enrollment as well as answer questions.

To take part, please select one of the dates/times found at https://bit.ly/NB_RoundUp. After registering, you will receive an email containing the meeting information link that will allow you to join by phone or computer. [*Note: The virtual meeting is optional for parents; additional communications with the same information will continue to go out.]

To enroll your child in North Branch Area Schools, visit:
https://bit.ly/NB_Enroll_A [100% digital option] or
https://bit.ly/NB_Enroll_B [paper enrollment option]

ATTENTION North Branch Bronco Families:

If your household income has changed, someone has lost a job, changed a job or the number of people in your household has changed, please submit an UPDATED Household Application for Free and Reduced Price Meals immediately.

A new application can be printed by clicking here http://www.nbbroncos.net/departments/food_service/food_service_documents or you can log in to your Family Access account and submit online. If you do not know your username or password, please email loginhelp@nbbroncos.net.

Congratulations to Suzanna Mazzoni, Nycol Deming, and Jalen Lewis for earning the Quest Merit Scholarship!

The Quest Merit Scholarship was started in 2006 by Ron and Carolyn Bower. The scholarship is still fully funded by the Bowers.

Suzanna plans to attend the University of Northern Ohio in Automotive Mechanics.

Nycol plans to attend Mott College to pursue a career in the healthcare field.

Jalen plans to attend the Culinary Institute of Michigan in Port Huron.

Congrats and best wishes in your future endeavors!

April 27 at 4:25 PM ¬∑

Mrs. Sieradzki's class worked so hard last week researching endangered animals. They were introduced to all the species on the endangered species list during class, then were assigned a research project! Students took time researching about an animal of their choice. They studied the habitat, prey, physical characteristics, and conservation status of their animal. They wrote up a report,and then were asked to either create a digital project or poster representing what they learned. They did a phenomenal job, and the projects look amazing! Monday, they used their class time to present their projects to their class. Awesome job boys and girls!
text:
#NBStrong #ALLIN

NBE
April 27 at 4:25 PM ¬∑

Mrs. Sieradzki's class worked so hard last week researching endangered animals. They were introduced to all the species on the endangered species list during class, then were assigned a research project! Students took time researching about an animal of their choice. They studied the habitat, prey, physical characteristics, and conservation status of their animal. They wrote up a report,and then were asked to either create a digital project or poster representing what they learned. They did a phenomenal job, and the projects look amazing! Monday, they used their class time to present their projects to their class. Awesome job boys and girls!

post_text: Student Art at Home- Shared by Mrs.Baksa
shared_text:
Rebecca Parsons Baksa
April 18 at 8:49 AM ¬∑

During our first week of official online classes, I assigned the "Happy Mail" project to my students. The idea behind the project was to make small cartoons of everyday objects, and then create speech bubbles that show feelings about social distancing and staying home. Students could then send them in the mail, text a pic, or post on social media to someone they miss. I loved seeing the ideas my students came up with, and wanted to share a few with you here.
The students' pieces follow this order: Regan Healy, Bryce Barkowska, Isabel Allen, Jessica Peters, Kinsey Cook, Rheagan Bower, Riley Younge, Tessa Meier, Tracy Ludescher, and Taea Stockwell. This is just a sample of all the happy mail that was submitted to Artsonia. Thank you students for continuing to create!#broncostrong

Dear Bronco Families,

Do you have a child, age 5-18, enrolled in school? If so, this message contains an extremely important link to information about the state's FOOD ASSISTANCE program.

Michigan is providing the Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer Program (P-EBT) to eligible families for temporary funding to address emergency food needs and avert financial hardship for families affected by the pandemic.

Families who are not already receiving food assistance benefits & meet eligibility will start receiving MDHHS notices in the mail late next week, with the EBT cards arriving by the first week of May.

Learn more: https://bit.ly/2xmLqO0

Good Afternoon North Branch Families,

This morning, Governor Whitmer issued an Executive Order suspending in-person K-12 instruction for the remainder of the 2019-20 school year. Rest assured, our administrative team and teachers have been preparing for Online Teacher Supported Instruction in addition to the Learning Packets that coincide with our NBAS Curbside Meal Program. We know you have many questions about what this means for your child. We will send out an additional communication letter this afternoon (approximately 6 p.m.) which will address many of those questions. Also, we have posted the Executive Order on our website which provides additional information.

Thank you for your continued patience and support as we work diligently to provide the best education possible for all of our students.

North Branch Leadership Team

Wonderopolis is a great way to get elementary & middle school students reading & learning! Students read to learn the answer to questions across various subjects. For example: How Long Have Schools Had Sports Teams? What are Zombie Worms? What is a Rhombicosidodecahedron? Who Was the First Casualty of the American Revolution? and more!

The site has a built-in text reader (if needed) as well as an optional follow-up "Did You Get It" quiz, word study fun, extension activities & more.

Visit: https://wonderopolis.org/

Dear NB Community:

We have had an overwhelming response this evening to the food program & learning materials. The district has worked tirelessly to prepare all we can in this unprecedented situation. We are sorry to report that the district is unable to provide any more meals and learning materials this evening. We are sincerely sorry for any inconvenience this may have caused our families, especially those who have been waiting patiently in line. We will do what we can to continue to provide food & instructional materials. Please look for more detailed communication on this from the district tomorrow. Once again, thank you.
